        <custodhist id="ref2">
            <head>Provenance</head>
            <p>Transfer from Rand School Archives, 1963.</p>
        </custodhist>
        <accessrestrict id="ref3">
            <head>Access Restrictions</head>
            <p>Open for research without restrictions. Series II: Eugene V. Debs Scrapbooks, has been microfilmed as Series III of The Papers of Eugene V. Debs, 1934-1945 (MCA, 1983); patrons must use microfilm (R7107).</p>
        </accessrestrict>
        <scopecontent id="ref8">
            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p>The Tamiment Clippings Scrapbooks contain newspaper clippings on a wide variety of individuals and topics. (There is a card index to the scrapbooks in the Tamiment Library Reading Room). The Eugene V. Debs scrapbooks contain clippings, magazine articles, leaflets, a large collection of obituaries, and miscellaneous materials collected by Eugene and Theodore Debs for reference purposes. (For a more detailed description, see: 
                <emph render="italic">The Papers of Eugene V. Debs, 1834-1945: A Guide to the Microfilm Edition</emph> (MCA, 1983), which accompanies Tamiment microfilm series R7107.) Both scrapbook series document the labor and socialist movements in the United States and in New York City, related civil liberties and civil rights issues, and opposition to World War I.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <bioghist id="ref7">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>The Tamiment Library Clippings Scrapbooks were compiled by the staff of the Meyer London Memorial Library of the Rand School of Social Science (1906-1956), the New York City workers education institution associated with the Socialist Party of the United States of America. The Eugene V. Debs scrapbooks were compiled by Debs and his brother Theodore, who served as his brother’s secretary and office manage. Eugene V. Debs (1855-1926) was a railroad labor organizer and later a leader of the Socialist Party, and was its candidate for U.S. president (1900-1912 and 1920), the last time while imprisoned for his opposition to U.S. entry into World War I.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <arrangement id="ref5">
            <head>Arrangement</head>
            <p>Arranged numerically within each series.</p>
            <p>Organized into two series:</p>
            <list type="ordered">
                <item>I, Tamiment Library Clippings Scrapbooks</item>
                <item>II, Eugene V. Debs Scrapbooks.</item>
            </list>
        </arrangement>
